{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bea9312c-5389-403d-bb8a-87cc538ec1fb","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are gone. Instead, use **`Window` lifecycle events**:\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (Window) |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` / `Backgrounding` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` |\n\nOverride `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribe to the events:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart logic */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep logic */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume logic */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\nAlternatively, subclass `Window` and override `OnCreated()`, `OnStopped()`, and `OnResumed()` for a pattern closer to what you had before.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"778f4720-56ff-4508-8989-cdec8f94055f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a straightforward knowledge question about the MAUI lifecycle API — I can answer directly without needing tools.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class. Specifically:\n\n- `OnStart` → `Window.Created` event or override `Window.OnCreated()`\n\n\n- `OnSleep` → `Window.Backgrounding` event or override `Window.OnBackgrounding()`\n- `OnResume` → `Window.Resumed` event or override `Window.OnResumed()`\n\nThe approach is to override `CreateWindow()` in your `Application` class and return a custom `Window` subclass, which gives you access to the full lifecycle event set: `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, `Destroying`, and `Backgrounding`.\n\nSo the mappings are: `OnStart()` maps to `Window.Created`, `OnSleep()` maps to `Window.Stopped` or `Window.Backgrounding`, and `OnResume()` maps to `Window.Resumed` or `Window.Activated`. Though MAUI still supports the legacy `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` methods on `Application` for backward compatibility, the Window lifecycle events are the recommended modern approach.","outputTokens":945,"requestId":"5014:D447C:1C8FA77:1F9A571:69FA910E"},"id":"94eb9bea-c3f7-40b0-9838-f6cecdfba57d","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:53:51.153Z","parentId":"aca0b65b-764e-4dd2-bafb-6ff5e906f912"}
